Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

No contact with Mark Compeau. Defendant must notify Clerk of Courts of current/updated address within 24 hours of release from custody.

2:59 PM Defendant Sarah Marie Dolsen appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Michael Hoffman appears with Defendant. Attorney Chad LaLor in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. Defendant indicates homeless. Mail goes to address on complaint. Court does not find probable cause on Count 1. Attorney Hoffman questions how causes 2 and 3 can exist without probable cause on Count 1. Court indicates did find probable cause on Counts 2 and 3. Attorney Hoffman waives further reading, pleads not guilty, asks for preliminary hearing. Court accepts plea. Dimisses Count 1.
State requests $400 cash, with conditions of no contact with Mark Compeau, Victim 1. Out on cash bond already on 2 open matters in douglas County. No stable address. 
Attorney Hoffman indicates lifelong resident of Douglas County, works locally. No missed court appearances. No money to post. Requests high signature bond. 
Court orders $500 cash, 2000 signature bond. Conditions of no contact with Mark Compeau.  Must update address within 24 hours of release.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for October 19, 2022 at 08:30 am.
